  "answer": "The specific supplication known as *Sayyid al-Istighfar* from Sahih al-Bukhari is not present in the provided sources, so you may want to independently verify its exact wording outside of these texts. \n\nHowever, the sources do contain other authentic, comprehensive supplications from the Prophet Muhammad that practically unify the three categories of Tawhid:\n\n**Tawhid al-Rububiyyah (Lordship and Creation)**\nThe Prophet consistently affirmed Allah's ultimate control and creative power in his prayers. He praised Allah as the \"Supporter of the heavens and the earth,\" the \"Originator of the heaven and the earth,\" and \"the best of Creators\" [1-3]. \n\n**Tawhid al-Uluhiyyah (Exclusive Servitude)**\nIn these same supplications, the Prophet pledged his absolute and exclusive servitude. He declared, \"Thou art my God. There is no god but Thee,\" and \"I am Thy bondman\" [1, 2]. He further anchored this practical devotion by stating, \"Verily my prayer, my sacrifice, my living and my dying are for Allah, the Lord of the worlds\" [2].\n\n**Tawhid al-Asma wa al-Sifat (Names and Attributes)**\nWhile affirming his status as a servant, the Prophet invoked Allah's specific divine names to seek forgiveness. He pleaded, \"Forgive all my sins, for no one forgives the sins but Thee,\" and explicitly called upon His attributes by praying, \"please forgive me and be Merciful to me as You are the Forgiver, the Merciful\" [3, 4].",
  "conversation_id": "b75c54d4-0ca8-4686-8f68-eef116d359e6",
